{% set schema = bolt.data.components['@bolt-elements-icon'].schema %}

{% set description %}
  Custom SVG can be used instead to render an icon that is not available in the design system.
{% endset %}

{% set notes %}
  <bolt-ol>
    <bolt-li>When creating a custom SVG, start with a 32px by 32px artboard in the design tool (Adobe Illustrator, Sketch, etc.).</bolt-li>
    <bolt-li>Make sure all layers have been converted to objects, meaning there is no stroke, only shapes with color fill.</bolt-li>
    <bolt-li>Combine all objects if they visually connect (i.e. create one big shape).</bolt-li>
    <bolt-li>Set the object&rsquo;s fill color to #151619.</bolt-li>
    <bolt-li>Set the widest side to 32px and center the icon within the artboard.</bolt-li>
    <bolt-li>Save the SVG and then use <a href="https://imageoptim.com/mac">imgoptim</a> or another tool to minify it.</bolt-li>
    <bolt-li>
    Lastly:
    <bolt-ol>
      <bolt-li>
        <strong>If you choose Twig usage:</strong> Add the relevant attributes <code>{% verbatim %}{{ attributes.addClass(classes)|without('aria-hidden') }} aria-hidden="true"{% endverbatim %}</code> to the <code>&lt;svg&gt;</code> HTML element and save it as a Twig file. Then you can display the icon using include statement by passing the icon source path to the <code>custom_icon_path</code> prop.
      </bolt-li>
      <bolt-li>
        <strong>If you choose HTML usage:</strong> Add <code>class="e-bolt-icon"</code> along with relevant modifier class for each prop, and the attribute <code>aria-hidden="true"</code> to the <code>&lt;svg&gt;</code> HTML element. Then you can display the icon using the modified <code>&lt;svg&gt;</code> markup.
      </bolt-li>
    </bolt-ol>
{% endset %}

